\pard\b\fs32 1. Introduction\par
\pard\b\fs28 1.1 Background\par
\pard\fs24\b0 In the last decade, data growth in recruitment ecosystems has become exponential. Every hiring cycle now generates vast amounts of unstructured resume data, job descriptions, skill requirements, and interview metadata. Traditional resume filtering methods cannot scale effectively in this environment due to manual effort, inconsistency, and low responsiveness. Big Data-driven systems and machine learning models solve this challenge by automating high-volume data processing and prediction tasks with measurable performance.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 1.2 Problem Statement\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Current candidate screening methods are often keyword-dependent, static, and difficult to scale. Many ATS tools provide limited insight into why a resume is filtered out. The key problem is to build a robust architecture that can handle large resume datasets, predict the most suitable job role in near real time, and generate personalized feedback that improves ATS compatibility.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 1.3 Project Objectives\par
\pard\fs24\b0 1. Build a scalable data pipeline for resume ingestion, cleansing, and storage.\par
2. Train an NLP-based machine learning model for role classification.\par
3. Integrate an ATS feedback module for practical resume enhancement guidance.\par
4. Provide API-first deployment for frontend and external system integration.\par
5. Ensure extensibility for distributed compute (e.g., Spark MLlib) in future versions.\par
\page

\pard\b\fs32 2. Literature Review or Survey\par
\pard\b\fs28 2.1 Evolution of Big Data Systems\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Big Data systems are typically characterized by the five Vs: Volume, Velocity, Variety, Veracity, and Value. Recruitment systems exhibit all five dimensions: millions of resumes (volume), continuous submissions (velocity), mixed formats including PDF and text (variety), noisy and inconsistent data (veracity), and decision-making utility (value). Modern pipelines therefore require distributed architectures, efficient indexing, and parallel processing.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 2.2 Machine Learning for Resume Classification\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Resume role prediction is framed as a multiclass text classification task. Conventional approaches include Naive Bayes, SVM, and Logistic Regression using bag-of-words or TF-IDF features. Although deep transformer models offer richer semantics, linear models remain strong in production due to interpretability, lower training cost, and easier deployment.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 2.3 ATS Analysis Research Direction\par
\pard\fs24\b0 ATS performance depends on lexical relevance, section completeness, measurable achievements, and role-specific keyword density. Studies indicate that combining rule-based checks with machine learning scoring provides better results than either approach alone. This project adopts this hybrid philosophy to provide both prediction and actionable correction feedback.\par
\page

\pard\b\fs32 3. Methodology \u38? Work Description\par
\pard\b\fs28 3.1 Data Acquisition and Integration\par
\pard\fs24\b0 The methodology starts by loading a validated base dataset and optionally merging additional backup datasets. Each source is schema-checked for required columns such as role and resume_text. Source-level traceability is retained for reproducibility. Duplicate role-text combinations are removed to reduce training bias and leakage.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 3.2 Data Cleaning and Feature Preparation\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Resume text is normalized by trimming whitespace, handling inconsistencies, and preserving meaningful terms. Labels are standardized to avoid class fragmentation. Role skill priors are then injected as weighted anchors to strengthen signal for underrepresented classes and sparse resumes.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 3.3 Model Design and Optimization\par
\pard\fs24\b0 A pipeline-based architecture is used: TF-IDF vectorizer plus Logistic Regression classifier. Training uses stratified split and Stratified K-Fold cross-validation to preserve class distribution. Hyperparameter tuning is performed through GridSearchCV with macro F1 objective, optimizing n-gram range, document frequency thresholds, regularization strength, and class weighting.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 3.4 Evaluation and Persistence\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Best-performing parameters and model scores are logged. The trained model is serialized for inference and training metrics are saved in JSON for experiment history, reporting, and model governance.\par
\page

\pard\b\fs32 4. Proposed Algorithm\par
\pard\b\fs28 4.1 Algorithmic Steps\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Step 1: Load base and optional external datasets.\par
Step 2: Validate mandatory schema and clean records.\par
Step 3: Merge, normalize, and deduplicate dataset.\par
Step 4: Inject role-skill priors (optional).\par
Step 5: Split data into stratified train/test sets.\par
Step 6: Build pipeline (TF-IDF + Logistic Regression).\par
Step 7: Run GridSearchCV with f1_macro scoring and stratified folds.\par
Step 8: Select best estimator and evaluate on validation set.\par
Step 9: Export trained model and metrics artifacts.\par
Step 10: Deploy model for API-driven real-time inference.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 4.2 High-Level Pseudocode\par
\pard\fs24\b0 Input: Datasets D, optional backups B, config C\par
Output: Model M, metrics R\par
\par
1. X = merge(load(D), load(B))\par
2. X = clean(X); X = deduplicate(X)\par
3. if C.role_priors_enabled then X = inject_role_priors(X)\par
4. (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test) = stratified_split(X)\par
5. pipeline = TFIDF + LogisticRegression\par
6. M = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, f1_macro).fit(X_train, y_train)\par
7. y_pred = M.predict(X_test)\par
8. R = evaluate(y_test, y_pred)\par
9. save(M, R)\par
10. return M, R\par
