\pard\b\fs32 7. Implementation \u38? Coding\par
\pard\b\fs28 7.1 Implementation Architecture\par
\pard\fs24\b0 The codebase is organized with separation of concerns: data layer, ML pipeline layer, API layer, and presentation layer. The model training module supports command-line options for data path, output path, backup ingestion, and role-prior control. This modularity enables controlled experiments and maintainable deployment cycles.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 7.2 Key Coding Components\par
\pard\fs24\b0 1. Dataset loader with strict schema validation.\par
2. Dataset merger with source traceability and deduplication.\par
3. Prior injection utility for role-specific lexical reinforcement.\par
4. Pipeline constructor for TF-IDF and Logistic Regression.\par
5. Grid-search training and best-estimator extraction.\par
6. Metrics exporter and model serializer for production use.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 7.3 API and Frontend Integration\par
\pard\fs24\b0 The application includes API endpoints for model health checks, role prediction, ATS scoring, and dataset generation support. Frontend modules provide resume upload, modal-based insights, and user feedback forms, enabling a practical full-stack deployment path.\par
\page

\pard\b\fs32 8. Result Analysis\par
\pard\b\fs28 8.1 Evaluation Criteria\par
\pard\fs24\b0 The primary optimization target is macro F1 score, selected for fair multiclass evaluation. Additional indicators include validation accuracy, precision, recall, and class-wise F1. This combination provides both aggregate and granular understanding of model behavior.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 8.2 Observed Outcomes\par
\pard\fs24\b0 1. Hyperparameter tuning consistently improves baseline model performance.\par
2. Role-skill priors improve class anchoring for shorter resumes.\par
3. Balanced weighting benefits minority class recall in imbalanced datasets.\par
4. Input quality strongly affects prediction confidence and stability.\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 8.3 Analytical Discussion\par
\pard\fs24\b0 The model is computationally efficient and interpretable, making it suitable for practical ATS workflows. However, lexical methods may underperform on semantically complex profiles. Continuous retraining, data enrichment, and controlled monitoring are required to preserve reliability over time.\par
\page

\pard\b\fs32 9. Conclusion \u38? Future Scope\par
\pard\b\fs28 9.1 Conclusion\par
\pard\fs24\b0 This project successfully demonstrates an integrated Big Data and Machine Learning framework for career role prediction and ATS feedback. It addresses scalability, reproducibility, and practical deployment requirements while maintaining interpretable outputs. The architecture supports both academic demonstration and real-world extension.\par
\par
